rounds.response:
Let me evaluate what Player 0 is proposing:

Their offer
- Gives me 10 Brick (value 23 × 10 = 230)
- Takes 5 Wheat (5 × 5 = 25) and 5 Wood (5 × 10 = 50)
- Net change to me: +230 – 25 – 50 = +155 value, and my Brick count would jump from 19 to 29.

No resource would fall below zero, so the deal is technically acceptable. The value increase is also quite large. However, since no time limit is specified for responding, I can try to bargain for even more within the same turn.

I will make a counter-offer that still gives me a nice bump while keeping the deal attractive for them.

[Offer: 10 Brick -> 7 Wheat, 3 Wood]

rounds.response:
I’ve looked at the situation:

- I currently have:
  – Wheat 24 (value 5 each)
  – Wood 17 (value 10 each)
  – Sheep 8 (value 12 each)
  – Brick 19 (value 23 each)
  – Ore 10 (value 40 each)

- Player 0’s rejected offer asked me to give up 10 Brick (230 value) in exchange for just 5 Wheat (25 value) + 5 Wood (50 value). That deal would have hurt my total value.

- My counter-offer—10 Brick for 7 Wheat + 3 Wood—was rejected, which tells me Player 0 either values Brick very highly or isn’t willing to give away Wheat/Wood right now.

Given that I have plenty of Brick (19) and Player 0 clearly wants it, the best way for me to increase my total value is to trade Brick for resources that are worth *more to me*—namely Sheep, Ore, or possibly more Wheat if the ratio is right.

**Plan**: Offer Player 0 some of my excess Brick in exchange for Sheep and/or Ore. Since Sheep and Ore are both worth more than Brick (12 and 40 respectively), even trading 1 for 1 is favorable for me.

**Next move**: I’ll propose a deal where Player 0 gives me high-value resources and I give Brick. Let’s test their willingness to part with Sheep first.

[Offer: 5 Brick -> 6 Sheep, 2 Ore]

Let me calculate what I need to improve my portfolio:

- Brick is my most abundant resource (19 units) and has only a modest value (23).  
- Ore has the highest value (40) and is currently scarce in my hand (10 units).  
- Sheep is also high-value (12) and I have only 8.

I’m willing to give away a bit more Brick than its “face value” if I can land both Ore and Sheep, because the combined value jump will more than compensate.

rounds.response:
Thought process so far (silent):

1.  Work out total present value
    Wheat: 24 * 5  = 120  
    Wood : 17 * 10 = 170  
    Sheep: 8  * 12 =  96  
    Brick: 19 * 23 = 437  
    Ore  : 10 * 40 = 400  
    ----------------------  
    TOTAL value now = 1 223

2.  What resources are “cheap” to me?  
    • Wheat (5) and Wood (10) are lowest-value holdings.  
    • Sheep (12) is next-low but I already have little (only 8).  
    • Brick (23) I have lots (19), so it is my most fungible card that is not the ultra-high Ore (40).  
    • Ore (40) is most valuable; I only have 10.  I want *more* Ore.

3.  What I would like to do  
    a. Increase Ore count (currently 10).  
    b. Convert surplus Wheat and Wood into something higher-value (Ore, or failing that Sheep/Brick).

4.  Constraints from earlier offers  
    • Player 0 already refused to give me Brick ↔ Wheat+Wood or my Brick ↔ Sheep+Ore offers, so a straight repeat will almost certainly be denied.  
    • He therefore seems averse to giving me Ore/S sheep when I’m proffering brick.  
    • We’ve only one turn left (implicit round-10 situation because “game lasts 10 turns”), so an either-accept-or-bust offer is needed.

5.  Simplest mutually-advantageous proposal  
    I only have 4 Wheat (after -5 Wheat/-5 Wood in the proposal) but that still leaves me enough of everything else.

    My goal: trim the *least valuable* cards (Wheat and Wood) to grab more Sheep/Ore.  
    Player 0 earlier *offered* 10 Brick for 5 Wheat+5 Wood.  That tells me he *wants* Wheat+Wood and is willing to part with Brick, the lowest of his own cards (in his perspective).  If I sweeten the ratio a bit, he may bite.

    Option: Give away *all* 10 of my lowest-value Wheat (5 each) and 5 of my Wood (10 each) in exchange for 11 Brick (I earlier wanted Sheep or Ore, but Player 0 rejected those).  The 11 Brick let me flip the utility: 11 * 23 = 253, for a bundle worth (10*5 + 5*10) = 100, I make 153 value gain straight up.

    However, Brain-storm alternative: give 8 Wheat + 2 Wood to keep Wood-count comfortable while still dumping the weakest resource.  8*5 + 2*10 = 60, ask for 6 Brick.  Player 0 valued 10 Brick at 5 Wheat 5 Wood before; scaling this, 6 Brick for 8 Wheat 2 Wood is *better* than a full 11-Brick-for-10-5 he initially proposed.

    Player 0 might now accept.

6.  Final message

[Offer: 8 Wheat, 2 Wood -> 6 Brick]
